default&#xa0;
defaultIn-town cycling
default10. 
defaultRoads i
defaultn 
defaultprovincial
default towns, whether nominally A-, B- or unclassified, are generally 
defaultcyclable
default. Traffic is slow, obstacles such as parked cars, turning vehicles, pedestrians
default, 
defaulttraffic lights, pedestrian crossings and speed bumps keep things that way, and motor traffic and bicycles can very easily co-exist.
default Motorists need to be aware that cycles have to go around drains and that sort of thing. Cyclists need to be aware that holdi
defaultng up a car for a few extra seconds can be very frustrating for the motorist.
default&#xa0;
default11. Cities have an extra class of road, the cross-city through route
default. It is
default the urban equivalent of a trunk road
default. These
default 
defaultroads 
defaultare highly dangerous
default. 
defaultI would not cycle on them. 
defaultTh
defaulte problem, as usual, is they were planned and constructed without thought to 
defaultbicycles
default as a means of transport and they make no concessions to the needs of cyclists. Some cities have attempted to retro-fit cycle lanes but these often stop when the going get
defaults tough, for example at junctions or whe
defaultre
default the carriageway is narrow, so 
defaultthey 
defaultmerely pay a token nod to cycling. 
defaultBad retro-fits like that do not decrease the danger. 
defaultThe road corridor, though, is often wide enough that a proper cycle route could be fitted,
default and if this were done such a route
default, whether on-road or not,
default would be safe.
default&#xa0;
default12. Road junctions are one of the least friendly aspects of cycling in towns and cities. Very many junctions have been designed without any thought to how a cyclist might negotiat
defaulte them. Some of the bigger roundabouts simply cannot be negotiated. 
defaultHaving o
defaultne of those in a route negates the entire route. There is usually room 
defaultto cater 
defaultfor 
defaultbicycles (and other light vehicles)
default if the road engineers had 
defaultconsidered
default them.
default Where the enginee
defaultring has gone out of its way to make life difficult for the bike rider there 
defaultare bound to be 
defaultproblem
defaults
default but I’ve yet to see a junction where a bike compatible design could not be implemented.
default That said, a minimally bike compatible design is not the same as a
default fair
default-
defaultfor
default-
defaultall design. I 
defaultcame across
default one junction 
defaultwhere 
defaultthe
default cyclist 
defaulti
defaults expected to push seven 
defaultcrossing buttons and wait seven times (14 minutes?) to go straight on. It’s no wonder 
defaultsome cyclists
default 
defaulttake their chance on
default the road.
default&#xa0;
default13. Cities and larger towns som
defaultetimes 
defaulthave
default mixed cycling and bus lanes. These are less than ideal 
defaultfrom the safety angle 
defaultsince bicycles and bu
defaultses are of very different sizes and have very different driv
defaulting characteristics: bu
defaultses accelerate well and cruise at 30mph but keep stopping, bicy
defaultcles accelerate
default poorly and 
defaultcruise at 10-15mph
default;
default so the two kinds of vehicle in the same lane get in each other’s way. The
defaultse mixed lanes
default are not so much 
defaultinherently 
defaultunsafe as frustrating and annoying
default, but frustration and annoyance breed danger
default.
